segments.text: I don't know.
I do remember when we were getting ready for military review, inspection, and all of that in the springtime.
And we were drilling out there across from Henderson Hall and the athletes were giving quite a bit of static to the Corps.
And of course a lot of those guys were in there because of compulsory ROTC and the draft and everything else.
It seems that night their swimming pool got blue and they needed to figure out who did it, but then they had to drain it and then scrape it and so they didn't get to use their pool.
to some people was Good Bull.
I didn't think that was Good Bull, but, uh, Ben loved the string.
Did you have any idea as to who did it?
I think I probably do if, uh, the guy, because I did get him to join the Century Club one time, so, uh, uh, it's amazing, too, uh, how much rank he got in the military, uh, but.
What about, surely there was Good Bull in the dining hall?
There was always Good Bull, you know, the, uh,

Back in the dining hall, and you probably heard this from other people, but we had both Sabisa and Duncan, and there was always the duty officer had to sit at a little table with the officer of the day, the bull, as we referred to the military officer.

And about once a year we would get a hare, as they'd say, and on the third wildcat, and I don't know what it would beat the hell out of with this or that or what, but the third wildcat, all the biscuits would come flying at the,

at the military officer and then all hell would break loose and we'd get restricted and everything else but it was kind of like when I was back here and retired from the military working in the commandant's office and I called the Colonel Scott who's now deceased but

his nickname was the goose and I asked Colonel Scott if he would come to a mini reunion we were having for the class 62 and Duncan and he said to me as serious as it could be they're not going to throw any of those deals at me again are they you know and so it is amazing some of the things you did which you thought was funny you know the of course there was always the

killing deer and skinning them in the shower and things like that because people used to go out hunting and things like that, but Everybody knew somebody but a lot of times the guys that just go out there in the in the river bottom or out here mainly going towards Navasota and and we always had the the students that

love to go out on the weekends and try to get snakes and other wildlife and it's always fun the getting the armadillos and painting them up and turning them loose in fact I guess it was about 72 when the University of Texas is a joke the students voted to change their name to the armadillo and the diggum dillas and then at the football game in Kyle Field all those maroon and white armadillos got released during the halftime but
Do you know anything about who it was that caught those?
No, wouldn't know anything about that.
No, I really don't, but I can remember not only did they let them out on the field, but some of them got released in the stands.
Were you back here then?
No, no.
Yes, yes, excuse me.
I was working assistant commandant then.
Did you have any idea that it was going to happen?
No, oh no, didn't know.
All we remember, we had the little bumper sticker
that the Aggies were giving them out that said, dig them dillas, and trying to make fun of Texas.
Had a lot of things happen, though.
I think I remember, of course, a lot more when I worked in the Commandant's office from 70-74 than I did as a student.

You know, you remember such things as one morning Colonel Parsons and I got a call to come over to the, and I don't know if we covered this the last time, but Colonel Parsons and I got called over to the
quad and it seems that this Texas Ranger was trying to find out

who had kidnapped Bevo and Bevo had been there earlier and I think John Adams does admit in his book that it was his squadron that he was CEO of but the thing I remember more than anything about that morning was the Texas Ranger had both Colonel Parsons and I he had our attention because he was talking about the penalty for cattle rustling and what it could do to these kids and of course what we were more interested in is you know
You don't want a kid doing this so-called good bull.
You don't want him getting into trouble.
And sure enough, one of the cadets there spoke up and said, well, Mr. Ranger, sir, I'm sure we can help you.
We don't want anything to happen to that animal either.
And all of a sudden, the ranger slowed up just a little bit because the kid was very nicely threatening the ranger.
If you want Bevo back, you better change your tone.
As you recall, how was the return of Bevo?
How did it come about?
I think that there was just some kind of agreement that came out of that, and then the disciplinary action would be handled here at the campus.
And I can't remember what actually happened.
Larry Williams was the person working discipline then in the Commandant's office, but I don't think it amounted to anything.
John Adams would definitely be able to tell you on that.
Somebody, and I've forgotten who it was that I interviewed,

was a part of the group coming back from Austin with them and they had a flat and a highway patrolman stopped and he said this interviewee said that in hindsight he felt certain that the highway patrolman was aware of what was going on but he helped them get their flat fixed.
Well you know there was the one time when they
A&M stole Bevo and rented a trailer over in Austin, which wasn't too smart to you all.

We had another one one morning when we got called over to Dorm 9, which was the band dorm, and somebody had filled all of the commodes on one end with cement in them, and thank goodness it wasn't quick drying.
We were able to get the physical plant over there, but this is just one of those typical games between one of the core units and the band.
But this is usually not what you call good bull when it starts running into money like that.
As you think back about all of the pranks that we would call good bull, do you remember any that resulted in real damage that cost
money or physical?
In the dining hall.
There have been sometimes when they've had food fights that really would cause a lot of expense.
I can remember

I guess it was the early 70, 70, 71 when we had one and then the outfits had to pay for the cash register which completely got ruined and you know it could really get carried away with just like water fights all of a sudden is what it would seem like it turned into.
During your student days of the campus organization,
other than the Corps, which ones do you think were held in the highest regard, like the band, MSC activities, singing cadets, and so forth?
Well, I think the singing cadets, definitely, if you're talking about being respected by the student body, back in my days, we had a lot of the kids in the Corps that were in the singing cadets.
And now it's very, very tough for a young man to be in the singing cadets because you're away from the Corps and there's just not...
I don't know, I would guesstimate there might not be but three or four in there to start with.
So I don't see the singing cadets now having that recognition and praise that they deserve.
I've often wondered why can't the young men and women in the Corps especially strive to have more students involved in, more Corps students involved in the student

government the singing cadets or you could just go right on into some of the vocal groups women's choir or others you know but I think I think the MSC was very very well respected and I think also our the rodeo club was in my days was was very respected in because we had a lot of students majoring in agriculture and silence sirloin this but now I don't know that you hear much about the
What did you and your buddies, when you were an undergraduate, what did you and your buddies really think about the band?
Oh, I think we started off being brainwashed.

If you weren't in the band, you know, we'd be in the dining hall, and then they'd say, beat the hell out of the Air Force, and the Army would jump up, and then beat the hell out of the Army and the Air Force, and then somebody would say, beat the hell out of the band, and everybody except the band would jump up.

And they made fun of the band, but I think really when you get down to it, you really respected them because they weren't your typical high school band students that you tend to remember from, especially a small high school, because most of them
would always tend to dominate a lot of the intramural sports, which in my days, probably the most important thing was who was the Class A champion or the Class B champion in sports.
And in the intramurals in your day, name the various sports you can recall.
Well, I ended up living intramurals and ended up being senior intramural manager.
But I think that the important thing back then

The points for the flag, whether you were civilian or were you a freshman or you were upperclassmen corps, intramural flag was probably the most important thing and points for General Moore intramurals had a good portion of the total points system.
And ping pong counted just as much as flag football.
Our softball in our days it was fast pitch softball and there were some tremendous athletes.
We had a lot of people, for an example, that were not, when they came here, were small or were not big enough to play varsity sports.
But after about three years of eating in Sabisa and dunking and working out all the time, they were tremendous athletes.
We played basketball, we had ping pong, we had horseshoes, we had volleyball, we had tennis.
Our track was more of an open track.
I remember right it didn't count for the intramural points, but we had open golf.
But your ping pong, tennis, football, basketball, bowling counted also just as much.
And each outfit in the corps or the civilian dorms had an athletic officer, athletic sergeant.
And you did not cancel or fail to show up for a match.
As you look back on that, what was significant in the long run for the young participants in intramurals?
Well, I think probably what was the long run, it was important.

I know when I came back here, and had been here for a good while, and who you know, Dean Adams out at the vet school, came up to me one night at a reception, and one of the first things he said, I was a

Junior in the outfit when he was freshman, and he was real good at that fact he won the intramurals high hurdle and But he came to me He said but did you know we won class a football the year you left and I said I didn't know they had now here's a very distinguished professor and everything but he knew what was important back then and I think that might be a little bit of an example it taught us two or three things it taught us of course winnings important, but
We also learned how to lose, but even more, most of these were team efforts.
And you had to practice, and intramurals were probably more important than anything.
You got away from the so-called core crap or the class crap when you got out there.
Most of the people that came out in the outfits, especially upperclassmen, worked with the underclassmen.
It was a time to be just a...
relive those high school days.
And again, a lot of the kids that played intramurals were not able to play in the 4A schools, which were the largest back then, but they got down here and they were studs.
Of all of the individual student offices or positions, which ones had the highest prestige when you were an Aggie undergraduate?
I think speaking from the Corps, company commander was the most prestigious position you could have, even though a lot of people say, well, you're on staff or you're Corps commander.
But a lot of people say, well, if you can't be Corps commander, you can do more good being the company commander because you are the boss.
And you have a chance to influence a lot of people.
So I think from around the campus, if you ask, in my days, we had a lot of students here.
We probably had 7,000 students.
And when you think that you only have 72 coming into the RVs each year, that's a small portion of the student body.
So it was a respected, but not
now like it is where a good portion of that junior class is going to be in the RVs.
And being Corps commander had more prestige than being student body president.
Oh, I think so.
I think so.
I think you can just look at today and see the commandant of cadets, you know.
I mean, when you look at salary range, what the person makes and everything, but the person that comes in here, that is a very respected position, and it brings a lot of benefits with it.
Were you aware when you were a student that secret fraternities existed?
I'd heard it, but I didn't know anything about it.
Had you heard that there was one or more than one?
Just one.
And of course, over the years, you hear about everything from the TTs to the sticks and all of that.
I can truthfully say that I...

didn't believe it, you know, and as a student, you know, the mole men were another group you heard mentioned, but then as years go on and you come back here, you find out that, hey, maybe this did exist, you know.
Turn it back on.
Okay.
Home for you...
It was Jacksboro, Texas, which was... How did you get to and from Jacksboro?
I hitchhiked the entire time.
And normally that took about how long?

Normally, normally I would say you would leave here, you could plan on six hours roughly, although sometimes it took a lot longer and I can only remember one time being picked up and the entire trip without having to get out.
You made a non-stop?
Non-stop one time, yeah.
But I will tell you, though, Haskell, that the interesting thing, though, back then, even though hitchhiking, though, we all talked like we hitchhiked more than we really did.
We had hometown clubs.
We were very active in them.
And the people from Jacksboro, we tended to belong to Wichita Falls because anybody going to Wichita Falls had to go through Jacksboro, basically.
Now, if you shared a ride with somebody else in the car, was it...
known from the beginning that everybody would share in paying for the gas?

I think it I think it depended on who the upperclassmen was and if they had if they had money some of them would hustle rides for that and then there were others that would not charge you you know and especially if you were a freshman
It was customary, you know, you get 15 miles off campus, I believe it was 15 miles, then you dropped handles.
Well, I'll never forget, there was one guy that was head yell leader for a while my freshman year, Smokey Hyde, and then Smokey got relieved, but Smokey wouldn't drop handles, you know.
You caught your ride out at Eastgate from here?
If you were hitchhiking, yes, you'd go out to Eastgate, and then we, of course, just like the old story, you'd get in line,

The problem that we had, being from Jacksboro, and there were five of us, and one had a car, but if we were going, we'd have to go from Waco to Stephenville on Highway 6, go that way, or really to HICO.
And then six cuts off, we'd go on up 281 to Stephenville.
But you get out in that part of that open country and it becomes night, it's hard to catch a ride.

But if you went to Fort Worth, then you'd get out and you'd have to get out to the Jacksboro Highway, which meant lots of times you'd have to carry your bag for about a mile, mile and a half, just walk across there.
And how did you learn where was the best place to get the ride in Fort Worth?
Well, yeah, well, get out on the...
get out on the Jack Sparrow Highway.
That was just the normal pass down.
As you say word of mouth, somebody would tell you what to do.
But the biggest problem that you had was if you ever tried to hitchhike and not wear your uniform.
Because if you wore your uniform, and we all had the old suitcase with the block T, as they say on it, and people pick you up and
Now, you might end up in that 240 miles with 10 rides.
You know, that's because an old farmer will see you.
You know, and they stop and carry you.
You may be just going 10 miles down the way.
All right, share with the machine some.

some hitchhiking stories funny serious well we uh we'd laugh a lot today you know sometimes you uh you might get picked up in a in a new cadillac and then the next thing you know the next car you're riding in the back of an old truck the problem is sometimes it's pretty darn hot or pretty darn cool especially if you're trying to get back in the fall for a
hometown football game.
We had drill on Saturdays, so it made it pretty rough.
It had to be something special, so you had that opportunity to go home.
So you didn't go home very much, but I guess only one time in the five years I was in college I ever rode with somebody where I was about halfway scared.
You know, just kind of a weird, weird person.
Were they driving too fast?
No, no, you just thought something was a little strange about this person, you know.

And then you didn't worry about the people that were picking you up just like they didn't worry really about the people they were picking up, especially if we had uniforms on, you know, and everybody...

Some of the stories you'd be you know, whether you in the military, but most of them in Texas and you because from From here to Waco for an example You didn't have a lot of people that didn't know about Texas A&M driving on on highway 6 You threw a lot of rocks at fence posts.
So Gary Halter and I have thrown a lot of rocks at fence posts together Oh, yes, I mean at times I
There's a couple of times when you're coming back and you'd pull into what was East Gate.
Back then you could see Dorm 1 and Dorm 2 and in conversation they'd usually ask, where do you live?
You just say over there and they'd drive over there and drop you off.
And I've had people that were going out of their way when you especially get up in the North Texas area that would go 30 miles out of the way to drop you off there in your hometown.
I've also been dropped off at Bowie when they were supposed to be going through Jacksboro and maybe they got into the cider somewhere and then, you know, you really get home late, you know.
And how did you and your buddies get dates?

Well, I think I can remember one episode that I'm sure a lot of people have told you about that go into my post office box and dear 5611, I'm 5611 and this was from Tessie and of course we had a court trip every year either TCU or SMU and
A lot of blind dates and no telling how many marriages came about or marriages to their friends, but there were a lot of dates.
Most of the time, somebody knew somebody in a dorm or a sorority, and we would have group parties in Austin or Huntsville or something like that.
I know we had one my junior year.
We had one freshman, Fish Duncan,
Eddie Duncan had a blind date with Linda Bird Johnson.
She was a senior in high school and that was an interesting time because again LBJ, all the way with LBJ was the slogan.
In fact, I remember the Baylor game, my Baylor game.

my junior year when we were playing, we were off the subject, but we were playing Baylor and Waco and this plane came over and dropped these leaflets and that's when Lyndon Johnson was running for both Vice President and Senator and the leaflets said, don't be half safe and you opened it up and it said, strike LBJ twice.
But anyway, back on the blind dates, back on the blind dates,

everybody either had a sister or their girlfriend wanted to fix somebody up and it was not hard to get a date from the standpoint of a weekend or something and because a lot of guys didn't want because so many guys didn't have any money you know they worked and and uh to come to school and so uh there was always the opportunity to have a date with someone this uh
outfitmate that had the blind date with Linda Berg.
Was this in Austin?
It was in Austin.
She was visiting a friend for the year ahead of her as a freshman in this sorority at Texas and so we ended up, we must have had 25, 30 guys go over there and had dates with sorority.
We did this a lot to Huntsville.
dorms, just different places.
Houston, the nursing, there was always somebody that was going with a nurse at Houston, so if it was Rice or the Houston game, there'd be 15 of those nurses and
What did this guy say about the date?
You remember?
Oh, Linda Berg?
I don't know.
What I do remember, which I don't know if it can be printed, but what was funny the next morning, or Monday morning, is the only time I've ever heard the term freshman fart off.
You know, you did not make fun of freshmen.
That was just, you could, upper class, now freshmen could, but one of the upperclassmen had a freshman go down and blow the whistle and said, fish Duncan went all the way with LBJ, you know.
Which was not true, I know, but still.
But we did have a lot of opportunities, no matter what.
Now, the girls in College Station and Bryan, that was another story.
Unless you happened to have a guy in your outfit that was going with one, and then that could open up the door to maybe have a date with a local girl.
There weren't that many.
There were not that many, and most of them did not even think about dating, unless they met them at church.
And that was the best way for somebody to actually get to know good families and get to know... Did you go to church here?
I went to the Methodist church here over A&M Methodist.
Describe their...
A&M student activity?
Well, they had the MYL, and the problem that I had my freshman year, I was in dorm two, the other side of the campus, and I usually didn't go on Sunday night.
I'd try to go Sunday.
I came down here, started my freshman year, I had 12 years perfect attendance in Sunday school, so I did go to Sunday, didn't go to the...
Down here as much as I should have, but again, I tried to go on Sunday mornings.
But did you go on Sunday night much?
Not much, mainly because of CQ and the dorm, and there were people like Bo that was a little more active in MYF and things.
Was religious emphasis week still going here when you were a student?
I've got to admit, I don't remember.
I'll tell you, I think it was very interesting in the core of the outfits.
I was in the pre-vet outfit, and I think we had a pretty strong Christian base in that outfit.
Most of the people were
were just really good people.
Now some of the outfits were pretty crude, pretty raunchy, a lot of filth, and I think the unit that I was in the entire time
Pretty darn clean cut.
I can remember when I was a freshman, upperclassmen coming in and they had a raffle.
And it went from one to a dollar.
And the numbers one to a hundred.
And if you won first prize, it was a trip to LaGrange.
Second prize would be a fifth of scotch.
So when you figure it out, those guys took in $50.
And I'll never forget John Sullivan and Robert Davidson.
They were from Galveston, next room.
They made us all enter.
And we were all hoping.
and praying that we didn't get the LaGrange trip, you know, even though there were a lot of guys, or we'd go over there every weekend.
But I remember, interesting, John Sullivan drew a one
had to pay a penny and then they drew again and he got a two.
So we still laugh about that today.
In fact, John and his brother support the General Moore Award now to this day.
But I think that we had a number of guys in my outfit that went to church and I always remember when I was having a problem

as freshmen academically and everything else, and this sophomore who I thought was about halfway mean came in one night and knew I was having problems, and he started talking to me and said, well, have you considered praying about it?
And then all of a sudden, you know, I'd been here about a month and a half, and then I saw this guy as human, you know.
For the first month and a half, I hated every upperclassman, you know.
If you had a date here on campus to a football game or something or other,
Where did you and your buddies take your dates after that event?
Well, most of the time there was not a lot of places to go out here to Franklin's.

in my days you could go out to you could go out there you go to a movie the places like that but there just wasn't a lot of places to go out you know I guess if if you find the people that did drink a lot and went out and this and that they probably went to different places you know but there just wasn't a lot of wasn't a lot of places probably the
most interesting place to go and you'd never take a date was to Guyon Hall to the movies here, you know, because of all the wisecracks, but.
Yeah, as student indulgences, what were the folks you knew about, what were they drinking?
Oh, most people when I was in school, it was beer.

You know, every once in a while they'd talk about if you were having a big event or something, you'd go out here to Whiskey Bridge, to Jones Bridge, you know, and they'd buy something or get somebody to buy.
But beer was the, and that was before the keg beer as such, you know.
But beer seemed to be the drinking.
What brands were they drinking?
Well, there was definitely Jackson Pearl back then, you know, and you had Slits.
Was Shiner popular?
Shiner was, I never remember Shiner being popular here.
Of course, it had its popularity in Texas and then later.
But I've got to tell you, I'm probably the wrong guy to be talking to because I just went in the Dixie Chicken for the first time about two years ago for a chicken fried steak.
And smoking, what were people smoking?
I remember every outfit would have a guy that gave away the three little cartons of cigarettes, a little four or five to it.
And I remember it seemed like Lucky Strikes and Camels were about the two I remember because I didn't smoke.
And almost nobody smoked a pipe.
There would be, it was a junior privilege to smoke a pipe in the mess hall, dining hall, but very few people did it, or a cigar.
senior privilege.
I can't remember if it was junior or senior, but it may have been a senior privilege.
I believe it was a senior privilege to smoke a cigar in the dining hall, except on the very formal one night when all the waiters would sell cigars at the table.
Even freshmen could smoke.
And then didn't sometimes it, was it in a football game or at Yale practice that
some group smoked cigars?
It probably was.
I don't remember that.
Again, all of this kind of goes back to what outfits and did.
I think if I remember right, it was a sophomore privilege either to chew gum on campus or maybe a junior privilege to smoke cigarettes on campus.
Did you and your buddies

even know the word marijuana no no no i know my first trip to vietnam is when i first started seeing problems with marijuana and that was in 66 and then when i went back in 68 i saw that heroin had become a serious problem with the young gis
But I don't remember we remember you hear people talk about it, but I don't ever remember hearing anybody having problems in the 58 through 60.
I'm sure they did but I don't didn't know anybody
